Report the balances applicable to the following counterparties
* RBA - a public financial corporation that has responsibility for monetary policy, issuing banknotes, holding Australia's international reserves and providing banking services to the Commonwealth.
* Other central bank institutions including APRA
* Banks - refers to corporations, in relation to which an authority under subsection 9(3) is in force and which holds a consent under section 66 of the Banking Act 1959 to use the word bank; it includes development banks and foreign banks licensed to operate in Australia under the Banking Act 1959; but does not include merchant banks (record as non-bank financial intermediaries) and non-resident banks (report as non-resident counterparties).
* Other ADIs - refers to corporations, in relation to which an authority under subsection 9(3) is in force, but which do not hold a consent under section 66 under the Banking Act 1959 to use the word bank.
* RFCs - refers to corporations registered under the Financial Sector (Collection of Data) Act 2001 that are classified as Categories D and other and cash management trusts and includes money market corporations (also referred to as "merchant banks") (D); pastoral finance companies, finance companies and general financiers (Other); and cash management trusts. RFCs exclude intra group financiers registered under the Financial Sector (Collection of Data) Act 2001 Category I (record as private trading corporations). A list of corporations registered under the Financial Sector (Collection of Data) Act 2001 and their classification is available on request.
* Central borrowing authorities (CBAs) - corporations established by State and Territory governments to provide finance for government authorities and to manage their surplus funds and includes New South Wales Treasury Corporation (NSW TCorp); Treasury Corporation of Victoria (TCV); Queensland Treasury Corporation (QTC); South Australian Government Financing thority (SAFA); Western Australian Treasury Corporation (WATC); Tasmanian Public Finance Corporation (Tas Corp); Northern Territory Treasury Corporation (NT TCorp); and ACT Treasury.
* Financial auxiliaries - corporations and quasi-corporations engaged primarily in activities closely related to financial intermediation, but which do not themselves perform an intermediation role including fund managers as principal;stockbrokers; and insurance brokers.
* Securitisers - financial vehicles that issue short and/or long-term securities (called asset-backed securities) using specifically selected assets (e.g. mortgages, receivables). They provide backing (collateral) for the securities and generate the payment streams necessary to fulfil interest and principal requirements for investors.
* Unit trusts - includes mortgage, fixed interest and equity unit trusts but excludes property and trading trusts.
* Other financial intermediaries - all financial intermediaries other than central bank institutions, depository corporations, insurance corporations, pension funds, CBAs, securitisers and unit trusts. This includes economic development corporations owned by governments; co-operative housing societies; investment companies; and common funds including cash common funds.

